public abstract class ComposablePredicate<T>
extends Object
implements Predicate<T>

Abstract implementation of Predicate. It provides four methods to compose predicates:

  • and
  • or
  • xor
  • negate

Method Detail

and

public ComposablePredicate<T> and(ComposablePredicate<? super T> other)
Returns a new ComposablePredicate evaluating to true if each of its components evaluates to true. The components are evaluated in order, and evaluation will be "short-circuited" as soon as a false predicate is found.

If you want to and-compose Predicates that do not extends ComposablePredicate, you should have a look on Predicates.and(Predicate...).

Parameters:
other - the other component to and-compose.
Returns:
a new ComposablePredicate evaluating to true if this and other evaluates to true.

or

public ComposablePredicate<T> or(ComposablePredicate<? super T> other)
Returns a new ComposablePredicate evaluating to true if any one of its components evaluates to true. The components are evaluated in order, and evaluation will be "short-circuited" as soon as a true predicate is found.

If you want to and-compose Predicates that do not extends ComposablePredicate, you should have a look on Predicates.or(Predicate...).

Parameters:
other - the other component to or-compose.
Returns:
a new ComposablePredicate evaluating to true if this or other evaluates to true.

xor

public ComposablePredicate<T> xor(ComposablePredicate<? super T> other)
Returns a new ComposablePredicate evaluating to true if it contains an odd number of components evaluating to true.

Parameters:
other - the other component to xor-compose.
Returns:
a new ComposablePredicate evaluating to true if this or other evaluates to true, but not the twice.

negate

public ComposablePredicate<T> negate()
Returns a new Predicate being the negation of this predicate, i.e., the returned predicate will evaluate to true when the original one evaluated to false and to false when it evaluated to true.

Returns:
the negation of this predicate.
